<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910613-0063</DOCNO><DOCID>910613-0063.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Official of Polifly   Financial Is Accused   Of Fraud, Conspiracy</HL><DATE>06/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   PFLY</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Office of Thrift Supervision charged aformer official of Polifly Financial Corp. with fraud andconspiracy in connection with $6 million in losses at itsPolifly Savings andamp; Loan Association, New Milford, N.J.   The thrift office alleged that Robert K. Hartmann, aformer director and general counsel for Polifly, fraudulentlyconveyed assets worth at least $10 million to his childrenand wife &quot;in an effort to put the assets out of the reach offederal regulators.&quot; The thrift office said it is seeking atotal of $8.2 million in restitution from Mr. Hartmann andhis wife, Patricia, and their four children, as well as Mr.Hartmann's law partner, David Van Dam.</LP><TEXT>   There was no answer late yesterday at Mr. Hartmann's hometelephone. Mr. Van Dam couldn't be reached for comment.   The thrift office said that Mr. Hartmann, who resigned asa Polifly director early last year, approved loans tocompanies in which he secretly invested. The office said thatMr. Hartmann and his wife held substantial interests in atleast nine different companies that received loans of morethan $59 million from Polifly, which has roughly $570 millionin assets. Mr. Van Dam, also a former general counsel, wasaccused of concealing the Hartmann interests while acting asa liaison between the thrift and the businesses.   The loans violate a thrift office regulation that limitscommercial loans to an Sandamp;L insider to $100,000.   The thrift office also seeks to ban Mr. and Mrs. Hartmannand Mr. Van Dam from working in a thrift or bank in thefuture. The thrift office said that the $8.2 millionrepresents the loss of roughly $6 million the thrift sufferedon the loans to the Hartmann companies, plus $2.5 million inprofits the Hartmanns earned as a result of the loans.</TEXT></DOC>